A method to determine cross-linking in polymers as a measure of thermal features such as heat-flow, melting point and reaction enthalpy is differential scanning caliometry (DSC), [121, 143, 144]. Similar to chemical-based methods, this method does not allow spatially resolved measurements, works destructively and is time-consuming. A typical measurement cycle in the so called dual-run mode takes 2 x 45 min during which a defined heating profile is applied, [141]. A comparative study has shown that different approaches for referencing the measurements to other methods might apply and also that errors in the repeatability can be 10%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
